08396nam a22009615i 9783110327496DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20132004gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019394627  a(OCoLC)1013950402  a97831103274967 a10.1515/97831103274962doi  a(DE-B1597)211676  a(OCoLC)853259263  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aHV6431 4aHV6431 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a100  aCC 76002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17687:00aEthics of Terrorism & Counter-Terrorism /cGeorg Meggle, Andreas Kemmerling, Mark Textor. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (345 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhilosophische Forschung / Philosophical Research ;v300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tAbstracts -- tI. Terrorism & Counter-Terrorism Semantics -- t'Terrorism' as a Method of Terrorism -- tBenign Blackmail: Cassandra's Plan or What is Terrorism? -- tTerrorism and Guerrilla Warfare − A Comparative Essay -- tState Terrorism and Counterterrorism -- tTerror: The Neglected but Inescapable Core of Terrorism -- tTerrorism and Collective Responsibility -- tThe Unethical Rhetoric of Terror -- tII. Terrorism & Counter-Terrorism Ethics -- tPolitical Terrorism and the Rules of Just War -- tTerrorism, Just War and Right Response -- tTerrorism, Morality and Right Authority -- tTerror & Counter-Terror: Initial Ethical Reflections -- tCounter-Terrorism: Torture and Assassination -- tThe War on Terrorism: Its Justification and Limits -- tMorals in Terrorist Times -- tThe Ethics of Terrorism -- tIII. Terrorism & Counter-Terrorism Law and Politics -- tWar on Terrorism and the Crises of the Political -- tTerrorism as an Instrument of Liberation: A Liberation Ideology Perspective -- tNational Security, Terrorism, and Constitutional Balance -- tCriminal Justice After 9-11: ICC or Military Tribunals -- tLooking for Mohammed: Data Screening in Search of Terrorists -- tDoes the Suppression of Pro-Terrorist Speech Enhance Collective Security? -- tAfter 9-11 - A Paradigm Change in International Law? -- tBiographical Notes0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWe are supposed to wage war against Terrorism - but exactly what we are fighting against in this war, there is nearly no consensus about. And, much worse, nearly nobody cares about this conceptual disaster - the main thing being, whether or not you are taking sides with the good guys. This volume is an analytical attempt to end this disaster. What is Terrorism? Are terrorist acts to be defined exclusively on the basis of the characteristics of the respective actions? Or should we restrict such actions to acts performed by non-state organisations? And, most important, is terrorism already by its very nature to be morally condemned? But, having a clear idea of what Terrorism is, would be only the beginning. Rational moral assessment still needs two further components: The relevant facts; and the relevant values and norms. Now, in a field where systematic disinformation has been even proclaimed to be the official policy, facts are obviously very hard to get at. This volume is mainly interested in Ethics: What's wrong with Terrorism? And what is morally right or morally wrong, respectively, with all the different means of Counter-Terrorism? What are the moral boundaries for waging war agains terrorism? What are the right ways of dealing with terrorists? And what about the alleged anti-terrorism wars on Afghanistan and Iraq? With contributions from Marcelo Dascal, Tomis Kapitan, Daniel Messelken, Seumas Miller, Olaf L. Mueller, Igor Primoratz, Charles P. Webel, Per Bauhn, Rüdiger Bittner, C. A. J. (Tony) Coady, Haig Khatchadourian, Georg Meggle, Peter Simpson, Carolin Emcke, Ralf Groetker, Laurence Lustgarten, Thomas Mertens, Aleksandar Pavkovic, Filimon Peonidis, Janna Thompson, Véronique Zanetti  aMode